snippet.textDisplay:
I have a lot of series or games that I adore and would do anything to get to see the characters doing stuff again but at the same time I understand why the thing had to end and am even happy that it ended where it did. I'm a firm believer that stories need to end somewhere and shouldn't be stretched on past their prime, no matter how much I love the characters and world. Because i'd so much rather enjoy them and see a fitting ending than watch them rot away into empty shells of the characters they used to be just to milk the fanbase more. My dad's always arguing that he wishes shows would continue and i'm like no thank god it didn't i'm happy with that ending.


examples that come to mind for me are nier automata, which I crave content for but also can't see anything else to do with the story and feel it was wrapped up perfectly. sure the world could be expanded but the story of the main characters is over. the podcast the adventure zone too, the creators talked a lot about the ending and were very firm in their decision to end it where it did and i'm glad they did. they had some side quest type live shows that fit fine, but the story is over and it's perfect.


sometimes worlds are so big that they can lend themselves to side stories or whatever after the main story, like i recently watched zootopia again and when it came out I really hoped they'd make another movie because the world was so big. now I feel like a second movie wouldn't work, but a tv cartoon of mini stories structured around judy and nick's police jobs could work. there's so much potential left to explore the big city they created, but there isn't a enough development left for the main characters to justify a whole new movie arc.


i think when it comes to continuing stuff, in the form of sequels or new seasons, it works if there's room to add something more that has meaning. more development to the story or characters that's justified. but if the characters have already completed their development arcs, and the world has been thoroughly explored, it's time to stop.


it's so much better to end with a nice bow than to keep going until the train falls apart.

snippet.textDisplay: Might be an unpopular opinion, but The Office lost steam long before Michael left. After Pam and Jim got married, the episodes slowly started to get less funny and less interesting. Before the marriage, just about every episode is jam-packed with really clever jokes, then after it just starts to feel a little goofy., and there's no main serious plot to drive any of it (other than Michael's romances, which were less interesting and even a little frustrating to watch.) Michael leaving was just a branch on the way down. Then it got even worse. Sort of like how The Simpsons golden era ended around season 8, but it stayed okay until season 12 or 13.

Before the marriage, just about every episode is jam-packed with really clever jokes, then after it just starts to feel a little goofy., and there's no main serious plot to drive any of it (other than Michael's romances, which were less interesting and even a little frustrating to watch.) Michael leaving was just a branch on the way down. Then it got even worse. Sort of like how The Simpsons golden era ended around season 8, but it stayed okay until season 12 or 13.

snippet.textDisplay:
Bojack Horseman just ended after being canceled and yet the ending is a true ending, the creator/writer of the series Raphael Bob-Waksberg, asked netflix that if they were planning on canceling it that they could give him a heads up so he could write a proper ending. Even before Bojack's planned cancellation Waksberg ended each season with a possible ending that also allowed for more season in case of a spontaneous cancel of the show. When the time came that netflix canceled the show, they went ahead and gave Waksberg the heads up he asked for therefore allowing for the best ending to my favorite show. It just goes to show how much Waksberg cared for his creation and although he said he was up to going for a few more seasons, he accepted the fate of the show and made a good ending instead of squeezing it to death or being petty about his show being canceled.


P.S.
Great Video Danny

snippet.textDisplay: Scrubs would have had one of the all-time greatest series finales if they hadn't decided to try and make it work without most of the main cast for another season. As for series that were gone too soon, I would say Reunion and A to Z. Reunion was a murder mystery on FOX that never even got to introduce the killer and A to Z was a show that was supposed to show a relationship between two characters from beginning to end, with each episode representing one letter of the alphabet. Therefore, the show only needed two 13 episode seasons to tell the whole story, and NBC cancelled it after one season.

snippet.textDisplay: Sense8 was a fantastic show that I think had 5 seasons planned out but was cancelled after Season 2. It was really heartbreaking to see all these characters I was so invested in just have their stories cut off. Never seen a show like it and the cinematography around the world was great. And even though we got that finale episode it was so rushed and seemed to try and fit those 3 extra seasons they had written into a two hour long special and it kinda sucked. I will never forgive Netflix lol
